{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Outgoing classification request includes the full fixed taxonomy label list.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is wiring between classifier logic and API client payload construction. A pure unit test of a helper can miss omissions introduced at module boundaries; full external HTTP is not strictly required if the integration test inspects the constructed client request object.","test_description":"Instantiate the classifier with a test double API client that records the exact request payload. Call classify() with a sample document, then assert the payload contains every configured taxonomy label (no missing labels, no truncation).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"If API returns a label outside taxonomy, module returns \"unknown\".","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The core risk is local post-processing/validation logic. This can be caught at a single object/function boundary by feeding an invalid returned label and checking normalization to \"unknown\".","test_description":"Call the label-validation/classification-result handling path with an API response containing an out-of-taxonomy label (e.g., \"medical\"). Assert returned value is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.7,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Same document yields same classification across repeated calls.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real LLM output stability (or proving mitigation against model non-determinism). Mocked deterministic responses can hide true variance from the external AI model.","test_description":"Run repeated real API classifications (e.g., 20+ calls) for the exact same document and configuration, then assert outputs are identical or within the module’s documented determinism contract (e.g., cache hit path). Fail if drift appears.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Token usage for a typical document remains within per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failure often comes from provider-side token accounting vs local estimates (prompt wrappers, system text, serialization effects). In-process mocks can under-report usage and miss budget overruns.","test_description":"Execute a real classification call for representative documents with production prompt format enabled. Read actual token usage from provider response metadata/billing fields and assert total tokens <= configured budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.55,"Agentic":0.09,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On rate-limit signal, module waits and retries instead of surfacing immediate error.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The risk involves real retry semantics across HTTP/API error signaling plus timing/backoff behavior. Pure mocks can hide incorrect status/header handling and sleep/retry orchestration bugs.","test_description":"Use a controllable HTTP test endpoint (or sandbox API) that returns rate-limit response first (e.g., 429/Retry-After) then success. Assert classify() eventually succeeds, retries at least once, and observed delay honors configured backoff policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
